        "node-t3":   "t3\nF000F000",
        "node-n12":  "n12\n55775577",
        "node-n123": "n123\n05770577",
        "node-f":    "f\nFA88FA88"
      },
      "panes": [
        {
          "type": "table",
          "title": "Sim bucket — every node in this cone, with polarity twin",
          "header": ["node", "sim", "~sim (polarity twin)"],
          "rows": [
            ["x0",   "<code>0xAAAAAAAA</code>", "<code>0x55555555</code>"],
            ["x1",   "<code>0xCCCCCCCC</code>", "<code>0x33333333</code>"],
            ["x2",   "<code>0xF0F0F0F0</code>", "<code>0x0F0F0F0F</code>"],
            ["x3",   "<code>0xFF00FF00</code>", "<code>0x00FF00FF</code>"],
            ["t1",   "<code>0x88888888</code>", "<code>0x77777777</code>"],
            ["t2",   "<code>0xAA00AA00</code>", "<code>0x55FF55FF</code>"],
            ["t3",   "<code>0xF000F000</code>", "<code>0x0FFF0FFF</code>"],
            ["n12",  "<code>0x55775577</code>", "<code>0xAA88AA88</code>"],
            ["n123", "<code>0x05770577</code>", "<code>0xFA88FA88</code>"],
            ["f",    "<code>0xFA88FA88</code>", "<code>0x05770577</code>"]
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Two rows match by polarity: <code>sim(n123) = ~sim(f)</code>. This isn't an independent discovery — it's exactly how f is built (the dashed output edge into f). The pair lands in the same bucket because the hash function strips polarity. The <em>useful</em> matches happen when a node from a <em>different</em> cone elsewhere in the network hashes here: that's the equivalence candidate resub then verifies."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "<strong>fraig's dynamic patterns.</strong> When SAT disproves an equivalence, the counterexample input vector is appended to every node's sim word (<code>fraigSim.c</code>). Each round of bucket-hashing benefits from a more discriminating pattern set, so spurious hits become rarer."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Bigger cuts: more words",
      "narrative": "For a k-input cut, 2^k input patterns are needed; that's <code>nWords = max(1, 2^k / 32)</code>. resub's default <code>nLeavesMax = 8</code> → 256 patterns → 8 words. dch uses 8 words by default for richer pattern coverage even on small cuts. Operations stay bitwise: <code>for (w=0; w&lt;nWords; w++) sim_z[w] = sim_p0[w] &amp; sim_p1[w];</code>",
